    \section*{Purpose}
    
        The purpose of this proposal is to appeal authorization to purchase the laboratory equipment for the study of Brewster’s Angle.
        
    \section*{Summary}
    
        On March 17, 2016, Dr. Neven Simicevic assigned our team to conduct the study of Brewster’s Angle.
        
        The principle of Brewster’s Angle is applied in improving items and devices we usually use, such as sunglasses, cars’ windows, and cameras; therefore, it has been highly interested by researchers. Undergraduate students in Science and Engineering majors are given opportunity to study this phenomenon through giving lectures and providing reading materials. However, in order to gain insight into Brewster’s Angle, it is necessary for students to have experience with measuring Brewster’s Angle using appropriate equipment. Through this study, not only students will acquire deeper understanding on the Brewster’s Angle but they also can practice their writing report skill on the subject.
        
        ...

    \section*{Introduction}
        Mention theory
        
        Snell's law:
        \begin{equation} \label{snell}
            n_1 \sin \theta_1=n_2 \sin \theta_2
        \end{equation}
        
        Apply Snell's law to Brewster's Angle $\theta_p$:
        \begin{equation} \label{brewster-snell}
            n_1 \sin \theta_p=n_2 \sin \theta_2
        \end{equation}
        
        Since Brewster's Angle properties indicate that $\theta_p + \theta_2 = 90^\circ$, we conclude:
        \begin{equation} \label{brewster's angle}
            \tan \theta_p = \frac{n_2}{n_1}
        \end{equation}
        
